THE Laelius was probably composed in June of the year 44 Β. c. From De Divinatione 2, 1, 3 it is clear that when that work appeared the Laelius had not yet been written, while the Cato Maior had already been published. In the De Officiis, which is not mentioned in the passage referred to above, there is a reference⁴ to the Laelius. Now the Cato Maior was com- posed in the spring of 44 Β. c., and the De Officiis in the follow- ing November.2 As Cicero was travelling during July and August, while September and October were occupied by the De Officiis, we may suppose that the Laelius was written in June of the same year.⁸ “
